Learning Objectives

The purpose of this lesson is to demonstrate the concept of bootstrapping when you have enough data to do so.

Learning Outcomes

In addition to the outcomes from Lesson 6 below, the student will generate bootstrap sample datasets, run a model and store model results from each sample, then obtain predictions from each stored model run’s coefficients, and display those predictions in a matrix plot.

The student will be able to manipulate data frames to get data ready for plotting.

The student will explore how data within a single variable is distributed (histogram).

The student will be able to generate box plots to compare values of a variable within two or more categorical groups (box, bar plots).

The student will be able to generate plots showing how one numeric variable’s values change with the values of another numeric variable (scatter plot).

The student will be able to run a simple model describing a theoretical relationship between two or more variables. Model examples include a t-test, a regression, an analysis of variance (ANOVA), and a generalized linear model.

The student will merge predictor data (independent or explanatory variables for each site) to bird count data to test for a relationship between bird abundance (the dependent variable) and an independent variable.

**Wild Trax data set: Modified_Lattitude_(TEWA)and(WTSP)_main_report**

The data we are looking at consist of detections of Tennessee Warbler (TEWA) and White-throated Sparrow (WTSP) per recording at each ARU station. There is one recording per hour within a 24-hour period at each station on a particular date, with one or more individuals per species detected per recording. The intent is to look at how detections of SWTH change over a 24-hour cycle and ideally how the relationship between time of day and song activity varies with latitude. Note: not all of the recordings have been transcribed yet, so there are some recordings with “NONE” as the species detected.

Our observations will be individual recordings. Each observation will have a count for each possible species in the dataset. Note: the variable individual_order may be better as max(individual_order) will give us the number of distinct individuals thought to be in a recording.

Manipulating data using tidyverse functions

Summarize individual counts of each species at each site in each recording using dplyr and tidyr while keeping everything on a single 2-d data frame.

songs_per_recording_TEWA<-ToD_TEWA_WTSP.birdsonly%>%
  #filter(location=="R-P15-19-103")%>%
  group_by(location, recording_date_time, species_code, latitude, longitude)%>%
  summarize(songactivity=sum(individual_count))%>%
  pivot_wider(names_from="species_code", values_from="songactivity")%>%
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), ~replace(., is.na(.), 0)))%>%
  select("location", "recording_date_time", "latitude", "longitude", "TEWA")
write.csv(songs_per_recording_TEWA, file="output/TEWA_songs_per_recording.csv")

indivs_per_recording_TEWA<-ToD_TEWA_WTSP.birdsonly%>%
  group_by(location, recording_date_time, species_code, latitude, longitude)%>%
  #filter(location=="R-P15-19-103")%>%
  summarize(indivs=max(individual_order))%>%
  pivot_wider(names_from="species_code", values_from="indivs")%>%
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), ~replace(., is.na(.), 0)))%>%
  select("location", "recording_date_time", "latitude", "longitude", "TEWA")
write.csv(indivs_per_recording_TEWA, file="output/TEWAindivs_per_recording.csv")

Histogram suggests non-normal distributions of Tennessee Warbler song activity and number of individuals. Variance in song activity is much larger than mean value, suggesting that we should model it with a negative binomial distribution. Variance ~ mean for number of individuals, which could be modelled with a Poisson distribution.

Run a Simple Model

Data exploration suggested that Tennessee Warbler song activity varied slightly as a quadratic function of Julian day.

songs_per_recording_TEWA$JDAY<-(songs_per_recording_TEWA$JulianDay-mean(songs_per_recording_TEWA$JulianDay))/sd(songs_per_recording_TEWA$JulianDay)

songs_per_recording_TEWA$JDAY2<-songs_per_recording_TEWA$JDAY^2

mod<-lm(TEWA~JDAY+JDAY2, data=songs_per_recording_TEWA)
summary(mod)

Regression results also suggested that Tennesse song activity varied as a quadratic function of Julian day, although a bimodel distribution is another possibility, and Julian day only explained a small amount of variance.

How well does the data meet the statistical assumptions of regression?

res<-resid(mod)
plot(fitted(mod), res)
abline(0,0)

There is a lot of variance heterogeneity (bad!) since the residuals vary a lot more as the size of predicted values of song activity increase.

qqnorm(res)#create a Q-Q plot for the residuals
qqline(res)#add a straight diagonal line to the plot

Larger predicted values’ residuals deviate from the Q-Q line, Though not that bad

We can try transforming the response variable to see if it improves the regression results but data independence will still be an issue.

songs_per_recording_TEWA$TEWA.log<-log(songs_per_recording_TEWA$TEWA+0.1)

Square-root transforming or log-transforming the data does not improve the model output much. R-squared values are slightly higher after transformation but variance is still very heterogeneous.

A generalized linear model that assumes a non-normal error distribution in song activity might fit better.

mod4<-glm(TEWA~JDAY+JDAY2, data=songs_per_recording_TEWA, family=quasipoisson(link = "log"))
summary(mod4)

There is some variance heterogeneity still but less than with linear regression and the pseudo-R2 (proportion of explained deviance) 0.1604028 is greater than the R2 explained by the regression.

Data exploration suggests that Tennesse song activity varies as a more complex function of day and night. Use a more complex model like a generalized additive model or a circular function.

Also keep in mind: all observations in these regression models are assumed to be independent but they come from four sites with multiple days in a row at a site. So mixed-effects models might be appropriate.

library(mgcv)
#library(gamm4)
thetaval=(var(songs_per_recording_TEWA$TEWA)/mean(songs_per_recording_TEWA$TEWA))

songs_per_recording_TEWA$TIME<-(songs_per_recording_TEWA$timeNumeric-mean(songs_per_recording_TEWA$timeNumeric))/sd(songs_per_recording_TEWA$timeNumeric)

GAM1 <- gam(TEWA ~s(JDAY, k = 3, bs = "cs") + s(TIME, k = 5, bs = "cs"),  data=songs_per_recording_TEWA, family=negbin(theta=thetaval, link="log"))

coef.gammB<-coef(GAM1)
#model.matrix(GAM1)

Create a prediction dataset for GAMs

timeNumeric=seq(from=0,to=23.95,by=0.05)
JulianDay=seq(from=113,to=240,by=1)
TIME=(timeNumeric-mean(timeNumeric))/sd(timeNumeric)
JDAY=(JulianDay-mean(JulianDay))/sd(JulianDay)

#songs_per_recording[songs_per_recording$timeNumeric==5,]
TEWA.tsss.jd<-expand.grid(intercept=1,
                             #latitude.F=c("N","S"), 
                             TIME=-0.5254806, #scaled value associated with timeNumeric=5.00
                             JDAY=as.numeric(levels(as.factor(JDAY)))
)

#get model matrix for GAM2 based on these variables in prediction dataset
TEWA.tsss.jdmm <- model.matrix(GAM1, TEWA.tsss.jd)

## predict and apply inverse link function: this gives a new matrix
TEWA.gam.pred <- (exp(TEWA.tsss.jdmm %*% coef.gammB))#take antilog?
Preds<-data.frame(TEWA.gam.pred)

Predicted effects

Try bootstrap. Note that the code chunk below has been set to eval=FALSE, so that it isn’t executed when the Markdown document is knitted.

table(songs_per_recording_TEWA$location)#955 recordings from the one location

fSampleNint <- function(dat) {
  dat %>%
    group_by(location)%>% 
    sample_n(100, replace=TRUE)
}#creates a sample of 100 observations from the dataset
d1<-fSampleNint(songs_per_recording_TEWA)
d2<-fSampleNint(songs_per_recording_TEWA)
d3<-fSampleNint(songs_per_recording_TEWA)

bs <- function(data, indices){#
  d<-fSampleNint(data)#, PKEY, 1
  #return(d$PKEY)
  try(GAM3 <- gam(TEWA ~s(JDAY, bs = "cs") + s(TIME, bs = "cc"), data=d, family=negbin(theta=thetaval, link="log")))
  try(coef.gamm<-coef(GAM3))
  try(return(coef.gamm))
}

library(boot)
a<-Sys.time()
songresults <- boot(data=songs_per_recording_TEWA,
                    statistic=bs, parallel="multicore",
                    R=100)
b<-Sys.time()
print(b-a)

CoefB <-t(songresults$t)
#get rid of columns with errors
CoefB<-data.frame(CoefB)
CoefB[] <- lapply(CoefB, function(x) as.numeric(as.character(x)))
#delete columns with NA values
all_na <- function(x) any(!is.na(x))
CoefB<-CoefB %>% select_if(all_na)
CoefB<-as.matrix(CoefB)
ncol(CoefB)
CoefBCI50 <- t(apply(CoefB, 1, quantile, c(0.5, 0.25, 0.75), na.rm=TRUE))
CoefBCI90 <- t(apply(CoefB, 1, quantile, c(0.5, 0.05, 0.95), na.rm=TRUE))
save(songresults, CoefB, CoefBCI50, CoefBCI90, file="output/boot100_TEWA_Aug2.RData")

Plot bootstrapped model results. Note that the code chunk below has been set to eval=FALSE, so that it isn’t executed when the Markdown document is knitted.

load("output/boot100_TEWA_Aug2.RData")
songs_per_recording_TEWA$date<-substr(songs_per_recording_TEWA$recording_date_time,1,10)
dates<-data.frame(unique(songs_per_recording_TEWA[,c("date","JulianDay","JDAY")]))
date_times<-data.frame(unique(songs_per_recording_TEWA[,c("date","JulianDay","JDAY","timeNumeric","TIME")]))

for (i in 1:nrow(dates)){
  Day<-dates[i,1]
  ordinal.day<-dates[i,2]
  songs.tsss.jd<-expand.grid(intercept=1,
                             timeNumeric=seq(from=0,to=23.66667,by=(1/3)),
                             JulianDay=seq(from=148,to=162,by=1)
  )
  songs.tsss.jd$JDAY<-(songs.tsss.jd$JulianDay-mean(songs.tsss.jd$JulianDay))/sd(songs.tsss.jd$JulianDay)   
  songs.tsss.jd$TIME<-(songs.tsss.jd$timeNumeric-mean(songs.tsss.jd$timeNumeric))/sd(songs.tsss.jd$timeNumeric)

  #Now limit predictions to those from a single date
  songs.tsss.jd<-songs.tsss.jd[songs.tsss.jd$JulianDay==ordinal.day,]
  
  JulianDay<-songs.tsss.jd$JulianDay
  timeNumeric<-songs.tsss.jd$timeNumeric
  str(songs.tsss.jd)
  names(songs.tsss.jd)
  
  songs.tsss.jdmm <- model.matrix(GAM3, songs.tsss.jd)#meantemp.s+moon.s+
  
  ## predict and apply inverse link function: this gives an n_new x B+1 matrix
  songpreds100 <- (exp(songs.tsss.jdmm %*% CoefB))#take antilog?
  
  ## calculate median and 95% CIs for predictions
  bp100.CI95 <- t(apply(songpreds100, 1, quantile, seq(from=0.025, to=0.975, by=((0.975-0.025)/95)), na.rm=TRUE))
  
  ## Use these bootstrapped predictions to generate heat maps, 3d plots, etc.
  
  songs.tsss.jd.bci<-cbind(songs.tsss.jd, bp100.CI95)
  songs.tsss.jd.bci$date<-Day

    preds.025.975<-songs.tsss.jd.bci[,6:101]
    for (k in 1:ncol(preds.025.975)){
      preds.025.975[,k]<-ifelse(preds.025.975[,k]>600,600,preds.025.975[,k])
    }
    tiff(paste0("output/matrix plots/TEWAsongrateXtime-",Day,".tiff"), units="in", width=6, height=4, res=300)
    matplot(songs.tsss.jd.bci$timeNumeric, 
            preds.025.975, 
            type="l", cex.axis=1.5, cex.lab=1.5,
            col="blue",#cividis(100),
            xlab="Time (24-h period)",
            #xlim=rev(range(preds.sitelevel$TSSS.hr)),
            ylim=c(0,70),
            ylab="# Tennessee Warbler Songs",
            main=paste0(Day))   
    dev.off()
}
